{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17646958","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17646958"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:38:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:38:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18219"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18219","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18219"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10933"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114295"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10933","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10933"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18219"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96295"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10201"},{"type":"tags","id":"10203"},{"type":"tags","id":"10209"},{"type":"tags","id":"11417"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25412"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25416"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114295","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114295"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following cell types releases osteoprotegerin (OPG)?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Mesenchymal stem cell","Preosteoclast","Mature osteoblast","Preosteoblast","Osteoclast"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMature osteoblasts\u003C/strong\u003E are responsible for the release of osteoprotegerin (OPG), a glycoprotein that plays a crucial role in bone metabolism. OPG prevents nuclear factor kappa-\u03b2 ligand (RANKL) from binding to its receptor RANK on osteoclast precursors by acting as a decoy receptor for the activator of RANKL. This inhibition of RANKL-RANK interaction reduces osteoclast differentiation and activity, thereby decreasing bone resorption.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMesenchymal stem cells\u003C/strong\u003E are progenitor cells that are able to differentiate into various cell types, including osteoblasts, but they do not release OPG themselves.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPreosteoclasts\u003C/strong\u003E are precursors to osteoclasts and are involved in bone resorption, but they do not produce OPG.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPreosteoblasts\u003C/strong\u003E are immature osteoblasts that are in the process of differentiating into mature osteoblasts. They do not release significant amounts of OPG until they mature.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOsteoclasts\u003C/strong\u003E are the cells responsible for bone resorption and do not produce OPG. Instead, they are influenced by the RANKL-OPG system, which regulates their activity.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Mature osteoblasts release osteoprotegerin (OPG), which is a key regulator of bone metabolism.","Osteoprotegerin acts as a decoy receptor for RANKL, inhibiting osteoclast differentiation and activity.","The balance between RANKL and OPG is crucial for maintaining bone homeostasis."],"references":["Hall JE. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2021. Chapter 80; pg. 996.","Khurana I, Khurana A, Kowlgi NG. Textbook of Medical Physiology_-E-book. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2019.","Clarke B. Normal bone anatomy and physiology. Clin J Am Soc Nephrol. 2008 Nov;3 Suppl 3(Suppl 3):S131-9.","Florencio-Silva R, Sasso GR, Sasso-Cerri E, Sim\u00f5es MJ, Cerri PS. Biology of Bone Tissue: Structure, Function, and Factors That Influence Bone Cells. Biomed Res Int. 2015;2015:421746."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96295"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18219"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96295","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96295"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-15T14:47:26+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-15T14:47:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10933"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114295"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4931","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4931"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Musculoskeletal","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"